Okay.

32
00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:55.740
That's better.

33
00:01:57.520 --> 00:02:00.280
Hello, everyone. Thank you so much for joining us. My name is Mike Foote.

34
00:02:00.320 --> 00:02:04.140
I'm a medical oncologist at Memorial Sloan Kettering in GI Oncology, and

35
00:02:04.200 --> 00:02:07.570
I'm thrilled to show you the interim results of our Phase 2 trial of

36
00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:11.600
neoadjuvant trastuzumab tucatinib combined with chemotherapy

37
00:02:11.680 --> 00:02:13.480
in locally advanced rectal carcinoma.

38
00:02:14.560 --> 00:02:15.580
These are my disclosures.

39
00:02:17.680 --> 00:02:21.220
Locally advanced rectal cancer is conventionally treated with tri-modality

40
00:02:21.300 --> 00:02:24.930
therapy, which consists of chemotherapy, chemoradiation, and

41
00:02:25.020 --> 00:02:27.780
surgery. This can be given in several different ways.

42
00:02:28.000 --> 00:02:31.880
When the chemotherapy and the chemoradiation are given before surgery, we term

43
00:02:31.920 --> 00:02:35.800
this total neoadjuvant therapy. Other centers may give the chemotherapy after

44
00:02:35.860 --> 00:02:36.460
surgery.

45
00:02:38.000 --> 00:02:40.300
Radiation and surgery have a lot of side effects.

46
00:02:40.540 --> 00:02:44.460
Over a third of patients with rectal cancer require a total mesenteric excision

47
00:02:44.500 --> 00:02:48.080
of their tumor, which is a very morbid procedure that necessitates a

48
00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:51.720
permanent ostomy bag. It's a life-changing experience.

49
00:02:51.800 --> 00:02:55.549
Radiation can cause permanent bowel, bladder, infertility, and sexual

50
00:02:55.600 --> 00:02:56.940
dysfunction in that region.

51
00:02:58.780 --> 00:03:02.710
Because of the side effect profile, many people around the world are trying

52
00:03:02.740 --> 00:03:06.720
to evaluate tumors after they receive total neoadjuvant therapy with

53
00:03:06.760 --> 00:03:10.360
chemotherapy and chemoradiation to see if the tumor still remains on

54
00:03:10.400 --> 00:03:14.220
endoscopy and on scans. If the tumor is absent on these

55
00:03:14.260 --> 00:03:18.200
assessments, then we term this a clinical complete response, and these patients

56
00:03:18.220 --> 00:03:20.720
can be safely managed without surgery.

57
00:03:20.800 --> 00:03:24.760
However, the majority of patients have residual disease even after these treatments

58
00:03:24.780 --> 00:03:26.360
and require the morbid surgery.

59
00:03:28.340 --> 00:03:32.160
We asked ourselves, looking at the landscape of targetable alterations in

60
00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:36.080
metastatic colorectal cancer, if targeting some of these alterations

61
00:03:36.120 --> 00:03:39.970
upfront in early disease could help improve clinical complete response

62
00:03:40.020 --> 00:03:41.710
rates to avoid surgery.

63
00:03:43.300 --> 00:03:45.820
We focused specifically on HER2-amplified tumors.

64
00:03:46.220 --> 00:03:50.120
HER2 amplification is a relatively rare event in metastatic colorectal

65
00:03:50.160 --> 00:03:54.080
cancer of about 4% of patients, but the prevalence in early-stage

66
00:03:54.120 --> 00:03:56.520
disease is not well known.

67
00:03:57.730 --> 00:04:01.360
Patients with HER2-amplified metastatic colorectal cancer that had

68
00:04:01.400 --> 00:04:05.190
progressed on standard chemotherapy treatments were treated with trastuzumab and

69
00:04:05.280 --> 00:04:08.880
tucatinib in this Phase 2 trial, and the results were very

70
00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:12.620
impressive. You can see here deep and durable responses for these patients,

71
00:04:12.760 --> 00:04:15.200
even after these tumors had progressed on chemotherapy.

72
00:04:15.840 --> 00:04:19.840
Notably, RAS mutations confer resistance to this treatment, so patients with

73
00:04:20.019 --> 00:04:22.580
KRAS-mutated tumors were not included on the study.

74
00:04:24.720 --> 00:04:28.220
Based on this exciting data, we saw a strong rationale for including these

75
00:04:28.320 --> 00:04:31.680
treatments upfront in patients with early-stage rectal cancer.

76
00:04:32.520 --> 00:04:36.380
Most HER2-amplified tumors are left-sided, so we thought there might be a

77
00:04:36.440 --> 00:04:38.850
concentration of HER2 amplification in these cancers.

78
00:04:39.800 --> 00:04:43.050
For patients that are symptomatic and need to go on treatment quickly, HER2

79
00:04:43.140 --> 00:04:46.820
amplification is very easy to test for with immunohistochemistry, FISH,

80
00:04:46.860 --> 00:04:50.830
and/or DNA sequencing. In breast cancer, HER2-targeted treatments are

81
00:04:50.940 --> 00:04:53.840
standard of care, and they've been very successful in the neoadjuvant setting.

82
00:04:54.310 --> 00:04:58.170
Notably in breast cancer, patients are treated for a pretty long time, a year or

83
00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:00.490
so, including before and after surgery.

84
00:05:00.940 --> 00:05:04.150
And finally, the data I just showed you was very impressive using trastuzumab and

85
00:05:04.180 --> 00:05:07.560
tucatinib in advanced metastatic disease that was HER2 amplified.

86
00:05:09.220 --> 00:05:13.160
So we asked ourselves, can neoadjuvant therapy with HER2 blockade increase

87
00:05:13.200 --> 00:05:16.360
the complete clinical response rates of locally advanced rectal cancer?

88
00:05:16.900 --> 00:05:19.040
And we evaluated this question in a number of settings.

89
00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:23.160
First, we had an introductory period of HER2 treatment alone for six weeks.

90
00:05:23.760 --> 00:05:27.500
We then added chemotherapy to this treatment to have an overall 21 weeks,

91
00:05:27.580 --> 00:05:31.240
about five months of total medical treatment for these cancers, and this was the

92
00:05:31.260 --> 00:05:35.050
main assessment. And finally, we asked this question in patients that also

93
00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:37.340
needed radiation after the completion of this therapy.

94
00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:42.440
This is the study schema. We enrolled patients that had locally advanced rectal

95
00:05:42.460 --> 00:05:45.740
adenocarcinoma that were HER2 amplified and KRAS wild type.

96
00:05:46.180 --> 00:05:47.880
All patients were mismatch repair proficient.

97
00:05:48.620 --> 00:05:52.190
We first gave them six weeks of trastuzumab and tucatinib, which target HER2 by

98
00:05:52.220 --> 00:05:54.330
itself, and then we had an exploratory assessment.

99
00:05:54.990 --> 00:05:58.469
And then finally, we added chemotherapy to this treatment to complete, again, about

100
00:05:58.480 --> 00:06:02.100
five months of total medical therapy.At week 21, patients were

101
00:06:02.120 --> 00:06:05.920
assessed with endoscopy, biopsy, CT scan, and rectal MRI to

102
00:06:05.960 --> 00:06:08.240
evaluate for the presence or absence of tumor tissue.

103
00:06:08.800 --> 00:06:12.050
If the tumor was absent on all these assessments, the patients were deemed to have

104
00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:14.440
a complete clinical response, which was the main endpoint of our

105
00:06:14.480 --> 00:06:18.300
study. If the patient had a complete clinical

106
00:06:18.320 --> 00:06:21.840
response, they were given the option for surveillance without radiation or

107
00:06:21.880 --> 00:06:25.630
surgery. If patients had residual disease, they were treated with

108
00:06:25.700 --> 00:06:27.580
standard chemoradiation or surgery.

109
00:06:30.060 --> 00:06:33.480
We hypothesized that addition of HER2 treatment in the early-stage setting would

110
00:06:33.540 --> 00:06:37.060
increase the complete response rate from the conventional 20%

111
00:06:37.100 --> 00:06:39.709
expected with chemotherapy alone up to 40%.

112
00:06:40.820 --> 00:06:44.480
To evaluate this hypothesis, we employed a Fleming two-stage design.

113
00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:46.780
In the first stage, 17 patients would accrue.

114
00:06:47.200 --> 00:06:50.080
If less than four patients had a complete clinical response, the study would end

115
00:06:50.120 --> 00:06:54.010
early for futility. If eight or more patients had a complete clinical response,

116
00:06:54.360 --> 00:06:57.980
the study would end for success. If between this number had a complete clinical

117
00:06:58.000 --> 00:07:01.040
response, we would enroll another 21 patients for stage two.

118
00:07:03.050 --> 00:07:06.700
Patients were assessed for HER2 amplification with standard methods,

119
00:07:06.720 --> 00:07:08.010
including immunohistochemistry.

120
00:07:08.120 --> 00:07:10.880
If patients had 3+ immunohistochemistry, they were allowed on the study.

121
00:07:10.900 --> 00:07:14.560
You can see an example here. If patients had 2+ staining and an

122
00:07:14.600 --> 00:07:17.400
elevated FISH ratio, they were also allowed to enroll in the study.

123
00:07:18.040 --> 00:07:21.380
And finally, we assessed for KRAS wild-type status using genomic sequencing.

124
00:07:21.440 --> 00:07:23.200
Again, all patients were KRAS wild type.

125
00:07:25.220 --> 00:07:28.500
We employed an institution-wide screening protocol for all patients with

126
00:07:28.580 --> 00:07:31.800
early-stage rectal cancer, which had really never been done before.

127
00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:35.760
We screened about 459 patients. Out of those patients, 11

128
00:07:35.820 --> 00:07:39.240
patients or about 2.4%, had HER2 amplification.

129
00:07:40.300 --> 00:07:42.340
We enrolled 10 of these patients in the study.

130
00:07:42.370 --> 00:07:45.240
You can see them here now as of our last data cutoff.

131
00:07:45.780 --> 00:07:47.800
Notably, this is a high-risk population.

132
00:07:47.840 --> 00:07:51.040
Seventy percent of the patients had clinical lymph node-positive disease, clinical

133
00:07:51.140 --> 00:07:54.580
stage three disease, and these were big tumors that were close to the sphincter.

134
00:07:54.660 --> 00:07:58.320
So a lot of these patients, the majority of them would have required a large

135
00:07:58.360 --> 00:07:59.680
rectal surgery on their tumor.

136
00:08:00.480 --> 00:08:00.760
Finally,

137
00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:04.580
70% of the patients had 3+ HER2 IHC.

138
00:08:06.620 --> 00:08:09.889
Of those 10 patients, nine of them completed the first six weeks of

139
00:08:09.920 --> 00:08:13.729
trastuzumab and tucatinib therapy alone. You can see them here on this slide.

140
00:08:14.140 --> 00:08:18.020
And we saw a very impressive overall response rate of about 78%

141
00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:19.850
with disease stability in the other two patients.

142
00:08:19.940 --> 00:08:21.280
This is much higher than expected.

143
00:08:22.480 --> 00:08:25.940
After the full course of medical therapy, including HER2 treatment plus

144
00:08:26.020 --> 00:08:29.640
chemotherapy, we had eight patients complete this as of the data cutoff,

145
00:08:30.080 --> 00:08:33.760
and half of the patients or 50% had a complete clinical response.

146
00:08:34.560 --> 00:08:37.961
I want to also note that no patient progressed on this treatment during this

147
00:08:38.000 --> 00:08:41.600
introductory period. No patient missed an opportunity later to get

148
00:08:41.640 --> 00:08:44.160
radiation or surgery because we extended this window.

149
00:08:45.840 --> 00:08:49.200
We evaluated the characteristics of patients that had a complete clinical response

150
00:08:49.260 --> 00:08:53.250
versus those that did not. The TNN staging was very similar between

151
00:08:53.280 --> 00:08:56.270
the two groups, but you'll note that the HER2 immunohistochemistry results were

152
00:08:56.300 --> 00:08:59.990
strikingly different. All the patients who had a complete clinical response had

153
00:09:00.020 --> 00:09:03.940
HER2 3+ staining, whereas only one patient without a clinical complete

154
00:09:03.980 --> 00:09:07.820
response had HER2 3+. And notably, this patient had a complete response

155
00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:09.780
after radiation was given to their treatment.

156
00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:13.820
We also evaluated the DNA quantity of HER2 using copy number

157
00:09:13.880 --> 00:09:17.840
analysis and found that this may be a more robust biomarker of patients that get a

158
00:09:18.140 --> 00:09:19.200
clinical complete response.

159
00:09:21.360 --> 00:09:24.100
Ninety percent of the patients had a grade one or two adverse event, but these were

160
00:09:24.160 --> 00:09:27.940
very manageable, and no patient had to discontinue treatment from it.

161
00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:29.740
Grade three events are highlighted here.

162
00:09:29.880 --> 00:09:33.340
The majority of them were transient liver enzyme increases that were reversible.

163
00:09:33.860 --> 00:09:36.340
No patient had a grade four or grade five adverse event.

164
00:09:38.120 --> 00:09:42.100
After the conclusion of their therapy, patients were closely monitored to

165
00:09:42.140 --> 00:09:43.260
evaluate for recurrence.

166
00:09:44.420 --> 00:09:48.120
Notably, four patients in our study did have recurrence after their initial period

167
00:09:48.180 --> 00:09:48.680
of complete

168
00:09:50.120 --> 00:09:53.900
medical therapy. Three of the patients had a complete clinical

169
00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:56.200
response and recurred within a median of four months.

170
00:09:57.300 --> 00:10:00.200
Now, just to take you through it, the first patient actually stopped their therapy

171
00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:02.910
early because they had a very early complete clinical response, so they didn't

172
00:10:02.910 --> 00:10:06.740
complete their full treatment. The second patient actually was lost to follow-up

173
00:10:06.800 --> 00:10:09.500
about halfway through, so he also did not complete his full treatment.

174
00:10:09.540 --> 00:10:12.120
This is for socioeconomic reasons.

175
00:10:12.500 --> 00:10:15.760
All of the patients had positive HER2 staining on the recurrent tumors.

176
00:10:15.800 --> 00:10:18.579
So there's a thought that maybe these patients just needed more time, akin to

177
00:10:18.600 --> 00:10:19.320
breast cancer.

178
00:10:20.380 --> 00:10:24.220
All recurrences were salvageable without surgery, and as of about two and a half

179
00:10:24.260 --> 00:10:28.110
years of median follow-up, 63% of patients have avoided surgery

180
00:10:28.300 --> 00:10:31.900
and have rectal preservation. We evaluated

181
00:10:31.940 --> 00:10:35.900
correlatives as well to see which tests might help predict

182
00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:38.080
for clinical response as well as track patient outcomes.

183
00:10:39.340 --> 00:10:43.200
We evaluated circulating tumor DNA, which was taken every six weeks for patients

184
00:10:43.250 --> 00:10:43.720
on the study.

185
00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:48.400
Overall, this was a great biomarker for tracking response and recurrence.

186
00:10:48.440 --> 00:10:51.660
You can see that patient two we talked about had a deep response to HER2 therapy

187
00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:55.180
but was lost to follow-up about halfway through the disease course and never

188
00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:59.000
cleared their ctDNA. Patient three had almost a near

189
00:10:59.120 --> 00:11:03.040
CR after medical therapy. You can see the ctDNA is still present but didn't

190
00:11:03.340 --> 00:11:07.000
go to nothing until after radiation was added, and they had a complete response.

191
00:11:08.240 --> 00:11:11.260
And finally, the last patient had a complete clinical response to medical therapy

192
00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:14.120
but later recurred. And you can see the ctDNA also spikes.

193
00:11:17.140 --> 00:11:20.860
We also evaluated an experimental PET MRI scan that used an 89

194
00:11:20.920 --> 00:11:24.500
zirconium trastuzumab tracer, which we hypothesized was specific for

195
00:11:24.560 --> 00:11:26.500
HER2-amplified tumor tissue.

196
00:11:27.770 --> 00:11:31.480
The first row, you see the patient at baseline had a highly avid tumor on their

197
00:11:31.500 --> 00:11:34.080
baseline scan, and you can see a big tumor on their endoscopy.

198
00:11:34.660 --> 00:11:38.230
And after they had a complete clinical response, you see the absence of avidity and

199
00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:39.260
resolution of the tumor.

200
00:11:41.520 --> 00:11:45.360
So the key take-home messages of this study so far, which is with early

201
00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:48.800
results, is that HER2 blockade was very active and provoked

202
00:11:48.820 --> 00:11:51.980
responses that were higher than we expected in

203
00:11:52.300 --> 00:11:54.520
HER2-amplified locally advanced rectal cancer.

204
00:11:55.110 --> 00:11:58.520
The response rate to this early introductory period of trastuzumab and tucatinib

205
00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:02.420
was 78%. Half of patients had a complete clinical response to

206
00:12:02.480 --> 00:12:06.044
neoadjuvant trastuzumab, tucatinib, and chemo.And

207
00:12:06.084 --> 00:12:09.564
63% of patients had a complete clinical response to trastuzumab,

208
00:12:09.604 --> 00:12:11.624
ducatinib, chemo, and chemoradiation.

209
00:12:12.544 --> 00:12:16.094
We saw strikingly that patients with 3+ HER2 IHC amplification

210
00:12:16.204 --> 00:12:19.824
predicted for their complete response, but we also have a continuous variable,

211
00:12:19.864 --> 00:12:23.504
which is the copy number of the DNA, which may be a more robust biomarker for a

212
00:12:23.524 --> 00:12:24.014
response.

213
00:12:25.024 --> 00:12:28.564
Notably, three patients who had a complete response recurred locally, but all these

214
00:12:28.604 --> 00:12:31.294
patients, as of the data cutoff, have been salvaged without surgery.

215
00:12:32.564 --> 00:12:36.124
Sixty-three percent of patients overall, after about two and a half years, have

216
00:12:36.144 --> 00:12:38.424
been managed non-operatively, and that's median follow-up.

217
00:12:39.164 --> 00:12:42.564
And we think that based on the recurrent tissue having HER2 positivity, that it may

218
00:12:42.584 --> 00:12:45.124
still be sensitive to treatment. So we may just need more time.

219
00:12:45.824 --> 00:12:47.204
Enrollment continues on our study.

220
00:12:48.004 --> 00:12:49.664
We've achieved the stage one endpoint.

221
00:12:50.924 --> 00:12:54.284
We'd like to thank all of the collaborators, patients, and sponsors for this

222
00:12:54.294 --> 00:12:56.524
study. I'd like to also especially thank Dr.

223
00:12:56.704 --> 00:12:59.354
Andrea Cercek for her leadership of the trial, as well as Dr.

224
00:12:59.524 --> 00:13:03.084
Luis Diaz, and I'm very excited to answer your questions and have a nice

225
00:13:03.104 --> 00:13:04.144
discussion. Thank you so much.

226
00:13:12.444 --> 00:13:14.744
Okay, questions for Dr. Foote.

227
00:13:15.284 --> 00:13:16.764
Oh, sure. Yeah, sorry, I'll stay up there.

228
00:13:17.344 --> 00:13:19.184
I see someone at the microphone over there.

229
00:13:20.384 --> 00:13:24.104
Hi. That's nice talk. Thank you. I may have missed this,

230
00:13:24.184 --> 00:13:27.804
but how many of the screened patients had the

231
00:13:27.844 --> 00:13:29.544
requisite HER2 threshold

232
00:13:30.584 --> 00:13:33.884
but were excluded because they had concomitant KRAS

233
00:13:33.904 --> 00:13:34.584
mutations?

234
00:13:35.804 --> 00:13:38.804
That's a great question. I had it as an asterisk, and I didn't draw attention to

235
00:13:38.824 --> 00:13:41.884
it. So no patient actually had a KRAS mutation. Isn't that interesting?

236
00:13:42.404 --> 00:13:46.264
So all of the early-stage rectal tumors that were HER2 amplified did not have a

237
00:13:46.304 --> 00:13:47.644
KRAS or NRAS mutation.

238
00:13:47.744 --> 00:13:47.754
Okay.

239
00:13:47.824 --> 00:13:49.164
So no patient was excluded for that.

